Oklahoma purchase credit card transactions project¶

The Office of Management and Enterprise Services in the State of Oklahoma has made its purchase credit card transactions available. This dataset contains information on purchases made through the purchase card programs administered by the state and higher education institutions.

#Creating separate Year and Month columns for future feature engineering
# Converting Transaction_Date and Posted_date from Python Object data type to datetime
df['Transaction_Date']=pd.to_datetime(df['Transaction_Date'])
df['Posted_Date']=pd.to_datetime(df['Posted_Date'])

df['Year_Month'].dtype
df['Year_Month']=pd.to_datetime(df['Year_Month'], format='%Y%m')
df['Year'] = df['Year_Month'].dt.year
df['Month'] = df['Year_Month'].dt.month
#Creating 'Week_Number' from 'Transaction_Date'
df['Week_Number'] = df['Transaction_Date'].dt.isocalendar().week

#Creating 'Day_of_Week' from 'Transaction_Date'
dayOfWeek={0:'Monday', 1:'Tuesday', 2:'Wednesday', 3:'Thursday', 4:'Friday', 5:'Saturday', 6:'Sunday'}
df['Day_of_Week'] = df['Transaction_Date'].dt.dayofweek.map(dayOfWeek)

Section 3 Feature Engineering ¶

Instructions:¶

  • Understand the data grain: each row is a cardholder (last name + first name)
  • An agency can have multiple cardholders. A corporate card (agency_name) can be used by many cardholders and these cardholders have to follow the corporation policy.
  • Intuition: One or two cardholders may abuse their corporate cards. If we compare a cardholder to his agency, we can find outliers.
  • The spending for a merchant category can be higher than others. It does not make sense to compare the spending of a merchant category to another. An agency can spend on various merchant categories, and you cannot claim anomalies just because the spending on one merchant category is higher than another.
  • Anomaly detection is about "comparing a transaction to a benchmark". What is the right benchmark?
  • So we will aggregate to the Aggrecy_Name level and card holder level then build features.
  • Common sense tells us the comparison should be at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_Category" level.

3.2 Feature 2: The ratio to the median amount ¶

  • Notice the only difference to the above code is "median".
  • The reason to use "median" is that median returns the central tendency for skewed number distributions. Extreme values (anomalies) can be detected by comparsion.

Conclusion:¶

Similar to the ratio to average amount, extreme spendings can be detected from the ratio comparing the amount to the median amount spent on the same merchant category. The median returns the central tendency for skewed number distributions so may be less affected by extreme outliers. The higher the ratio, the higher the likelihood of fraudulent transaction. The industry can determine appropriate benchmark ratio number for each merchant category.

3.3 Feature 3: The ratio to cardholder average amount ¶

Thought process:¶

  • From the intution that one or two cardholders may abuse their corporate cards, we can find outliers and anomalies from each cardholder and compare to his or her agency.
  • So I aggregate at agency and cardholder level to compute the average amount spent and compare with transactions.
  • The difference with feature 1 is changing "merchant category" to "cardholder".

Section 4. Modeling ¶

Thought process:¶

  • unsupervised modeling to find out anomalies (high likelihood of fraudulent transaction)
  • KNNs technique
  • split train and test data by 80/20
  • use the 14 created features
  • standardize train and test data

What is KNNs?¶

  • K-nearest neighbors is an unsupervised machine learning technique. It computes the Euclidean distrance of an observation to other obsevations and returns the distance of one data point to the neighboring data points.
  • The k-NN distance can be used in anomaly detection. The larger the distance to the k-NN, the lower the local density, and the more likely the data point is an outlier.
  • Once determine a reasonable boundary of K-NN distance (outlier score), can group the data into normal and abnormal cluster to find out the anomalies.

In [98]:
from pyod.models.knn import KNN
from pyod.models.combination import aom, moa, average, maximization

# Test a range of k-neighbors from 10 to 50. There will be 5 k-NN models.
n_clf = 5
k_list = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
# Just prepare data frames so we can store the model results
train_scores = np.zeros([X_train.shape[0], n_clf])
test_scores = np.zeros([X_test.shape[0], n_clf])
train_scores.shape
# Modeling
for i in range(n_clf):
    k = k_list[i]
    clf = KNN(n_neighbors=k, method='largest')
    clf.fit(X_train_norm)

    # Store the results in each column:
    train_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_scores_
    test_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_function(X_test_norm) 
# Decision scores have to be normalized before combination
train_scores_norm, test_scores_norm = standardizer(train_scores,test_scores)

Conclusion:¶

  • Using KNNs and aggragate average method to train the data, the model fount out 69 anomaly data point in test data. The average distance is large in the abnormal cluster than normal data cluster.
  • The 14 features are meaningful features to detect outliers.
  • Department of rehabilation services might have many fraudulent transactions.
  • LAWER L and Morey A might be the corporate card abusers in their agencies.

Section 5. Summary ¶

  • For this project, I come up with 14 derived features to build a unsupervised k-nearest neighbors model to detect fradulent credit card transactions.
  • From EDA, we can tell that the top two agencies with the most transactions are Oklahoma State University and University of Oklahoma. The top two most transacted merchant categories are stationery and book stores. And the month has the most transactions is October.
  • Getting the inspirations from reserach papers and prof, I use grouping aggregation, different time periods and ratios to create 14 features. Group by agency and merchant or group by agency and cardholder, and consider the effect of monthly transaction pattern and transactions on the same day. Based on practitioner literature and intuition, the larger the ratio, the higher the likelihood of the transaction being fradulent for each of the features.
  • To find out outliers and anomaly transactions, I built knns model (an unsupervised machine learning technique) using 14 derived features and group the data points into two clusters (one is normal transactions and the other is abnormal transactions). Before modeling, split the train and test by 80/20, train the model using training dataset and apply the model to test dataset to find out outliers in the test dataset. I aggreagte 5 knn models to achieve model stability, reduce overfitting risk, and then use average method to compute outlier scores. Using boundary outlier score of 1, the model identifies 69 likely fraudulent transactions in the test dataset. The 14 features are useful in detecting the anomaly data points. Finally, I explore a little about the abnormal transactions in the test dataset.

Limitation & future study¶

  • Due to high volume data and long training time, I just build 5 knns and use average method to reach the conclusion. The model can be improved by testing different n knns and aggregate with different methods.
